&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Auditor&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Let&amp;#39;s look at the meanings of the&amp;nbsp;given options:&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Auditor-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;a person who conducts an audit&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aviator-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;a pilot&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Collector-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;an official who is responsible for collecting money&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Radiator-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;a thing that radiates or emits light, heat, or sound&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, from the given meanings, we find that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Auditor&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the correct&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;one-word substitute.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;illicit&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the context of the sentence, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;smuggling and the trade was prohibited by law&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to activities that are illegal or not allowed by law.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the appropriate one-word substitute that captures the essence of being forbidden or illegal is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;illicit.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;illicit&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is used to describe something that is not legally permitted or authorized. (गैरकानूनी)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The port had become a hub for illicit trade, attracting attention from law enforcement agencies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Illicit&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 1) &lt;strong&gt;licit:&lt;/strong&gt; This term means legal or permitted by law (कानूनी or वैध).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 2) &lt;strong&gt;chaste: &lt;/strong&gt;This term generally refers to moral purity or simplicity and is often used in the context of abstinence from extramarital or all sexual intercourse. (पवित्र or शीलवान).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 3) &lt;strong&gt;legitimate:&lt;/strong&gt; This term implies being in accordance with the law or being legal. (वैध or कानूनी.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;the agreement of the verb with the subject&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Concord&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;means&lt;strong&gt; agreement or harmony between people or groups.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When we use the word in &lt;strong&gt;the context of grammar&lt;/strong&gt;, it has a similar meaning.&lt;strong&gt; Grammatical agreement between two parts of a sentence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An important language skill to master is subject-verb concord.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject-verb&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;concord&lt;/strong&gt; is when the &lt;strong&gt;subject of a sentence and the verb of a sentence agree.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the &lt;strong&gt;subject&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence is &lt;strong&gt;singular&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;verb&lt;/strong&gt; must be &lt;strong&gt;singular.&lt;/strong&gt; If the &lt;strong&gt;subject &lt;/strong&gt;of a sentence is &lt;strong&gt;plural&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;verb&lt;/strong&gt; must be &lt;strong&gt;plural.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For example:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The pages&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;are &lt;/strong&gt;held together by a staple.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the above example &lt;strong&gt;the subject&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;pages&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;the verb&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;are&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; are&lt;strong&gt; both plural&lt;/strong&gt;. They agree.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, from the above rule and example &lt;strong&gt;option 1 &lt;/strong&gt;is the correct answer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

